data.content:
Yes — for simple inline cases, use `[DataRow]` directly. It's cleaner and type-safe:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **complex types** that `[DataRow]` can't handle (it only supports compile-time constants), keep `DynamicData` but use tuples for type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
    new (string Input, bool Expected)[]
    {
        ("valid@email.com", true),
        ("invalid", false),
        ("", false),
    }
    .Select(t => new object[] { t.Input, t.Expected });
```

**Summary:**
| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| `[DataRow]` | Cleanest, type-safe, no boilerplate | Constants only (no objects/arrays) |
| `DynamicData` + tuples | Handles complex types, type-safe source | Still unwraps to `object[]` |
| `DynamicData` + `object[]` | Flexible | No type safety at the data level |

Use `[DataRow]` whenever your data is primitives/strings — it's the idiomatic MSTest approach.
